{
  "texts": [
    "Their existence lowers the barrier for smaller regimes or even non-state groups (like extremist organizations or wealthy individuals) to run sophisticated influence campaigns without needing an in-house capability (Carnegie Endowment for International Peace, 2024).",
    "Tech companies inadvertently are enablers when their AI innovations are repurposed.",
    "Companies like OpenAI, Google, and Meta are continuously improving AI's capabilities, which is beneficial for society in many ways, but also arms bad actors with better tools.",
    "There's a tension here: do these companies have a responsibility to restrict access to their models or build in disinfo safeguards?",
    "They have taken some steps (like OpenAI's content filters, or deepfake detection research by Facebook), yet the genie of general AI capability is out of the bottle and often open-source versions exist as well."
  ]
}